<div id="stitle" style="display:none;">Notebook Entry</div>
<dl id="n28050g"> <dt class="nbunit"><a name="n28" href="#n28050g">N28 (VI.D.6)</a>:  <a href="../../ff/fnbs/n28all.htm#n28050g"> 50(g)</a></dt> <dd> <blockquote> leperhouse / Theatre Royal</blockquote> <dd class="well"> <blockquote class="sources"><font color="green">[Townsend Street]</font> Meanwhile, another <mark>edifice</mark> arose in this quarter, a hospital <mark>for the use of the pilgrim lepers</mark> who were about to visit the shrine of St. James of Compostella, in Spain, who, while waiting for their ship, found comfort in this building, which, tradition says, stood on the site of the present <mark>Theatre Royal</mark>, and was afterwards the spot where Lord Roscommon erected a town residence, occupied later by Lord Ely. <small> A. Peter, <a name="APDF1" href="../../ff/fdra/fdex.htm#APDF1"><cite title="source">Dublin Fragments, social and historic</cite></a> (1925) 35</small></blockquote> </dd></dl>
